A Note to Parents and Students

If your child has an Ipad or Iphone, he or she can download the Canvas app to access classes and assignments. When asked for the school, enter Sunflower County Consolidated School District, then sign in using Clever, input your MSIS number for the username and password with 00, and then submit. You should see all classes, click on the class period and access zoom for live instruction during the appropriate time.

1st period- 8-8:50
2nd period-8:55-9:45
3rd period-9:50-10:40
4th period-10:45-11:35
5th period-1-1:50
6th period-1:55-2:45
7th period- 2:50-3:40

If you need assistance, call 6628841270.

North End Packet Pickup Directions (again this is for all schools on the North End):

Welcome to TEHS. To serve you more efficiently, we are asking you to park along Tiger Lane facing LF Packer Drive. (Tiger Lane is the side street leading to the football field.) Please do not leave your vehicles. We will collect your name, your scholar’s name and grade and give your the corresponding learning packet. This will be the only method and place for dissemination of learning packets. You are welcomed to pick up packets from 9 am to 2 pm. Thank you in advance for your patience and understanding.

post_text:
Parents, if your children are starting school virtually, you DO NOT need to pick up learning packets. Learning packets are only for those students who do not have any technology at home, or do not have internet access. Students who have technology DO NOT need learning packets. If a student is able to log on to Canvas, they do not need a learning pack. When the district’s student technology arrives, we will no longer utilize learning packets, because all students will have access to technology.

If you are not sure how to log into Canvas, please view the video on our website or social media page.

August 4 at 2:28 PM ·

After reviewing every school’s reopening plans, I am issuing an executive order delaying the start of some 7th-12th schools in hot spots. We are requiring masks in schools for teachers and students. We are also requiring masks at public gatherings statewide for two weeks—in a push to allow schools to safely reopen.

post_text: Hey everyone! As promised, here is guidance regarding selecting the 100% virtual learning option. For either option (hybrid or virtual), step 1 is to register! Copies of the waiver will be at each school, but you can certainly print them out if you have the capability. Stay tuned weekly for more updates as things could certainly continue to change! Thanks everyone for hanging in there with us, and remember to take the survey that was sent out Friday!

post_text:
Good afternoon everyone! Thanks to all who supported for our virtual meeting last night! 2 quick announcements coming up:

1) More information regarding the waivers for the 100% virtual option will be shared Monday, July 20, 2020. This will provide details with what you will need to do to select this option. In the meantime, be sure to register because you will still need to do that even if you choose the virtual option.

2) Parents of students in the district will receive a text message per child today that has a quick survey in it. Please take the survey for each child (if you have more than one)!

post_text: District leaders conducted a sample simulation of a school day from bus to arrival to building entry to bathroom use to dismissal and everything in between. As we continue planning, we recognize every single detail must be mapped out before we place any children in those positions. This allowed for more questions and more ideas to take back to the drawing board. Kudos to Principal Sonia R. Bolden and her staff for being extremely well-planned. We still have much work to do! Definitely tune into the Virtual Meeting tonight at 6!

post_text: IMPORTANT ANNOUNCEMENT: This will be shared on next week’s information blast but we wanted to go ahead and notify our stakeholders that the SCCSD Board of Trustees voted to change the 2020-2021 school year start date from August 6th to August 10th. Group A students would return on August 10th and Group B students would return on August 11th (groups are currently being formed). This will allow a full week of training for staff from August 3rd-7th.

Good news, good news!! Caps and gowns have arrived!! Therefore, pickup will be Thursday, May 21st, from 11:00 am until 2:00 pm. We will be on the front lawn. Students will drive up, and we will bring your items to you. PLEASE DO NOT GET OUT OF YOUR VEHICLE!! With safety being our FIRST priority, we WILL wear masks. ONLY students who ordered their cap and gown AND who do not owe a balance to Herff Jones will receive a gown. Please pay all remaining balances ASAP! THE GOWNS ARE YOURS TO KEEP!! During pickup, you will also receive your diploma as well as academic and athletic awards. See you Thursday!! CONGRATS CLASS OF 2020!! Remember, DO NOT get out of your vehicle. See you Thursday!!

post_text: Way to go Mr. Cochran and Delta Overload!!!
shared_text:
South Sunflower County Hospital
May 13 at 10:13 AM ·

How cool are these face shields?

These shields were made by a 3D printer that belongs to the Robotics Team at Gentry High School! (Go Rams! 🐏)

Thank you to the Gentry High School Robotics Team for thinking outside the box and sharing your cool and clever invention with our hospital staff, but most importantly, thank you for spreading acts of kindness throughout the community.

If you know anything about Indianola, you know that our community is quick to rise up and respond to the needs of its residents. We would like to thank everyone for all of the thoughtful outreach of support and help that you have so graciously given to us. From meals, donations, prayer, and words of encouragement, your support is impacting South Sunflower County Hospital greatly during this time. We are humbled, amazed, and so very grateful for this community we get to call ours.

shared_text:
Congressman Bennie G. Thompson
April 15 at 4:09 PM ·

Yesterday, it was announced that Mississippi’s schools will not reopen for the remainder of this school year due to the COVID-19 pandemic. Unfortunately, this means no prom, no senior class trips, and no commencement ceremonies for graduating seniors. Graduation day is the one day that all students dream of and work hard towards their entire life. I would like to use my social media platforms to recognize graduating high school and college seniors from the second congressional district of Mississippi. Please refer to the attached flyer for details and allow me to help celebrate your accomplishments. Class of 2020, I am very proud of you! The times may be uncertain but always keep the faith! #MS02Grads
text:
Seniors

Congressman Bennie G. Thompson
April 15 at 4:09 PM ·

Yesterday, it was announced that Mississippi’s schools will not reopen for the remainder of this school year due to the COVID-19 pandemic. Unfortunately, this means no prom, no senior class trips, and no commencement ceremonies for graduating seniors. Graduation day is the one day that all students dream of and work hard towards their entire life. I would like to use my social media platforms to recognize graduating high school and college seniors from the second congressional district of Mississippi. Please refer to the attached flyer for details and allow me to help celebrate your accomplishments. Class of 2020, I am very proud of you! The times may be uncertain but always keep the faith! #MS02Grads

post_text:
RLM Distance Learning
Access to Online Lessons and Assignments for Students Currently Enrolled in
Compact 8th Math, Algebra 1, or Geometry

Students in Mr. Catchings’ Compact 8th, Algebra 1, and Geometry classes will be able to access online lessons and assignments to remain engaged in the content. Instructions to access online learning and assignments:
1. Go to Clever.com and login as a student.
2. Access the Khan Academy application.
3. Once at the website, click "Sign up" and you will be automatically enrolled into the online classroom.
4. Assignments for videos to watch and questions to answer will be updated on a weekly basis.

Should you have any questions, feel free to email ocatchings@sunflower.k12.ms.us.

shared_text:
DrAdrian L Brown is with Carmen Alysia Wyms and Otis L Anthony II at Sunflower County Courthouse.
March 4 at 7:52 PM · Indianola, MS ·

This is the first year that a Mock Trial Team has been established at Gentry High School. Under the leadership, training, and guidance by the Honorable Judge Debra Giles and Law Clerk Ms Laura Cooper, the Gentry High School Mock Trial held it’s Mock Trial Showcase in preparation to compete in the Magnolia Bar Association Mock Trial Competition on Friday and Saturday of this week. Advisors Carmen Wyms, Rep Otis Anthony, II, and I have worked hard to prepare these students along with Judge Giles and Ms Cooper. We are truly thankful to have the full support of Superintendent Miskia Davis, Principal Willie Bolden, and Asst Principal Earnest Nelson. We are attempting to inspire the production of the next generation of lawyers in Sunflower County and the Mississippi Delta. On Friday and Saturday, we will be taking an “Ordinary Business Trip” as we seek to represent the Sunflower County Consolidated School District, Gentry High School, Indianola, and the Moorhead communities.

The Lady Tigers basketball team has made it to the semifinals of the 3A State Girls Basketball Tournament in Jackson!!!!! We will need all the support we can get to be in Jackson on Wednesday, March 4, 2020. So therefore, we will have spectator buses for the game. The game is at 9AM, and the buses will be leaving at 5:45am. It is your responsibility to be here on time to catch the bus. THE BUSES WILL LEAVE AT 5:45AM!!!!!The cost will be $20. ($10 for bus & $10 for admission into the game. All money will be due by Tuesday at 12noon....NO Exceptions. We (school) will purchase all tickets to expedite the process of getting into the game. $20 is due when you sign up to ride the bus. If you have any questions, please call school.

Today RLMJH’s exceptional education students and teachers visited China King Buffet for lunch. The purpose of this outing was to teach the students generalization and daily living skills. The students were able to choose their own food and fix their own plates. They also became great tippers to the waitresses in the restaurant. This outing gave them a sense of independence and pride. Shout out to their awesome teachers, Mrs. Hughes and Mrs. Polk for creating this opportunity for their students. A special thanks goes to our Principal, Christopher Turner for funding this outing for the students.
#WINNING
